    <p class="title is-5 mathjax">
      
        The Third Way to Interacting $p$-form Theories
      
    </p>
    <p class="authors">
      <span class="has-text-black-bis has-text-weight-semibold">Authors:</span>
      
      <a href="/search/?searchtype=author&amp;query=Broccoli%2C+M">Matteo Broccoli</a>, 
      
      <a href="/search/?searchtype=author&amp;query=Deger%2C+N+S">Nihat Sadik Deger</a>, 
      
      <a href="/search/?searchtype=author&amp;query=Theisen%2C+S">Stefan Theisen</a>
      
    </p>
    
    <p class="abstract mathjax">
      <span class="search-hit">Abstract</span>:
      <span class="abstract-short has-text-grey-dark mathjax" id="2103.13243v1-abstract-short" style="display: inline;">
        &hellip;-forms, where 3-<span class="search-hit mathjax">algebras</span> play a prominent role, are also discussed. The method to construct these models also easily recovers the modified 3$d$ Yang-Mills theory obtained earlier and straightforwardly allows for higher derivative extensions.
        <a class="is-size-7" style="white-space: nowrap;" onclick="document.getElementById('2103.13243v1-abstract-full').style.display = 'inline'; document.getElementById('2103.13243v1-abstract-short').style.display = 'none';">&#9661; More</a>
      </span>
      <span class="abstract-full has-text-grey-dark mathjax" id="2103.13243v1-abstract-full" style="display: none;">
        We construct a class of interacting $(d-2)$-form theories in $d$ dimensions that are `third way&#39; consistent. This refers to the fact that the interaction terms in the $p$-form field equations of motion neither come from the variation of an action nor are they off-shell conserved on their own. Nevertheless the full equation is still on-shell consistent. Various generalizations, e.g. coupling them to $(d-3)$-forms, where 3-<span class="search-hit mathjax">algebras</span> play a prominent role, are also discussed. The method to construct these models also easily recovers the modified 3$d$ Yang-Mills theory obtained earlier and straightforwardly allows for higher derivative extensions.
        <a class="is-size-7" style="white-space: nowrap;" onclick="document.getElementById('2103.13243v1-abstract-full').style.display = 'none'; document.getElementById('2103.13243v1-abstract-short').style.display = 'inline';">&#9651; Less</a>
      </span>
    </p>
    

    <p class="is-size-7"><span class="has-text-black-bis has-text-weight-semibold">Submitted</span> 24 March, 2021; 
      <span class="has-text-black-bis has-text-weight-semibold">originally announced</span> March 2021.
      
    </p>
    
    <p class="comments is-size-7">
