    <p class="title is-5 mathjax">
      
        On the density of eigenvalues on periodic graphs
      
    </p>
    <p class="authors">
      <span class="has-text-black-bis has-text-weight-semibold">Authors:</span>
      
      <a href="/search/?searchtype=author&amp;query=Kravaris%2C+C">Cosmas Kravaris</a>
      
    </p>
    
    <p class="abstract mathjax">
      <span class="search-hit">Abstract</span>:
      <span class="abstract-short has-text-grey-dark mathjax" id="2103.12734v1-abstract-short" style="display: inline;">
        &hellip;eigenvalues. We study the Kagome lattice to illustrate these techniques and generalize the claims to amenable quasi-homogeneous graphs whose acting group has Noetherian group <span class="search-hit mathjax">algebra</span> (this includes all virtually polycyclic groups). Finally, we provide a formula for the von Neumann dimension of eigenvalues of $\mathbb{Z}^d$-periodic graphs using syzygy module&hellip;
        <a class="is-size-7" style="white-space: nowrap;" onclick="document.getElementById('2103.12734v1-abstract-full').style.display = 'inline'; document.getElementById('2103.12734v1-abstract-short').style.display = 'none';">&#9661; More</a>
      </span>
      <span class="abstract-full has-text-grey-dark mathjax" id="2103.12734v1-abstract-full" style="display: none;">
        Using the Floquet-Bloch transform, we show that $\mathbb{Z}^d$-periodic graphs have finitely many finite support eigenfunctions up to translations and linear combinations and show that this can be used to calculate the density of eigenvalues. We study the Kagome lattice to illustrate these techniques and generalize the claims to amenable quasi-homogeneous graphs whose acting group has Noetherian group <span class="search-hit mathjax">algebra</span> (this includes all virtually polycyclic groups). Finally, we provide a formula for the von Neumann dimension of eigenvalues of $\mathbb{Z}^d$-periodic graphs using syzygy modules.
        <a class="is-size-7" style="white-space: nowrap;" onclick="document.getElementById('2103.12734v1-abstract-full').style.display = 'none'; document.getElementById('2103.12734v1-abstract-short').style.display = 'inline';">&#9651; Less</a>
      </span>
    </p>
    

    <p class="is-size-7"><span class="has-text-black-bis has-text-weight-semibold">Submitted</span> 23 March, 2021; 
      <span class="has-text-black-bis has-text-weight-semibold">originally announced</span> March 2021.
      
