    <p class="title is-5 mathjax">
      
        Automorphisms of the Lattice of Classical Modal Logics
      
    </p>
    <p class="authors">
      <span class="has-text-black-bis has-text-weight-semibold">Authors:</span>
      
      <a href="/search/?searchtype=author&amp;query=Soncodi%2C+A">Adrian Soncodi</a>
      
    </p>
    
    <p class="abstract mathjax">
      <span class="search-hit">Abstract</span>:
      <span class="abstract-short has-text-grey-dark mathjax" id="2103.12709v1-abstract-short" style="display: inline;">
        In this paper we analyze the propositional extensions of the minimal classical modal logic system E, which form a lattice denoted as CExtE. Our method of analysis uses <span class="search-hit mathjax">algebraic</span> calculations with canonical forms, which are a generalization of the normal forms applicable to normal modal logics. As an application, we identify a group of automorphisms of CExtE&hellip;
        <a class="is-size-7" style="white-space: nowrap;" onclick="document.getElementById('2103.12709v1-abstract-full').style.display = 'inline'; document.getElementById('2103.12709v1-abstract-short').style.display = 'none';">&#9661; More</a>
      </span>
      <span class="abstract-full has-text-grey-dark mathjax" id="2103.12709v1-abstract-full" style="display: none;">
        In this paper we analyze the propositional extensions of the minimal classical modal logic system E, which form a lattice denoted as CExtE. Our method of analysis uses <span class="search-hit mathjax">algebraic</span> calculations with canonical forms, which are a generalization of the normal forms applicable to normal modal logics. As an application, we identify a group of automorphisms of CExtE that is isomorphic to the symmetric group S4.
        <a class="is-size-7" style="white-space: nowrap;" onclick="document.getElementById('2103.12709v1-abstract-full').style.display = 'none'; document.getElementById('2103.12709v1-abstract-short').style.display = 'inline';">&#9651; Less</a>
      </span>
    </p>
    

    <p class="is-size-7"><span class="has-text-black-bis has-text-weight-semibold">Submitted</span> 23 March, 2021; 
      <span class="has-text-black-bis has-text-weight-semibold">originally announced</span> March 2021.
      
    </p>
    
