    <p class="title is-5 mathjax">
      
        Bracket structure on Hochschild cohomology of Koszul quiver <span class="search-hit mathjax">algebras</span> using homotopy liftings
      
    </p>
    <p class="authors">
      <span class="has-text-black-bis has-text-weight-semibold">Authors:</span>
      
      <a href="/search/?searchtype=author&amp;query=Oke%2C+T">Tolulope Oke</a>
      
    </p>
    
    <p class="abstract mathjax">
      <span class="search-hit">Abstract</span>:
      <span class="abstract-short has-text-grey-dark mathjax" id="2103.12331v1-abstract-short" style="display: inline;">
        We present the Gerstenhaber <span class="search-hit mathjax">algebra</span> structure on the Hochschild cohomology of Koszul&hellip;
        <a class="is-size-7" style="white-space: nowrap;" onclick="document.getElementById('2103.12331v1-abstract-full').style.display = 'inline'; document.getElementById('2103.12331v1-abstract-short').style.display = 'none';">&#9661; More</a>
      </span>
      <span class="abstract-full has-text-grey-dark mathjax" id="2103.12331v1-abstract-full" style="display: none;">
        We present the Gerstenhaber <span class="search-hit mathjax">algebra</span> structure on the Hochschild cohomology of Koszul <span class="search-hit mathjax">algebras</span> defined by quivers and relations using the idea of homotopy liftings. E.L. Green, G. Hartman, E.N. Marcos and O. Solberg provided a canonical way of constructing a minimal projective bimodule resolution of a Koszul quiver <span class="search-hit mathjax">algebra</span>. The resolution has a comultiplicative structure which we use to define homotopy lifting maps. We first present a short example that demonstrates the theory. We then study the Gerstenhaber <span class="search-hit mathjax">algebra</span> structure on Hochschild cohomology of a family of bound quiver <span class="search-hit mathjax">algebras</span>, some members of which are counterexamples to the Snashall-Solberg finite generation conjecture. We give examples of homotopy lifting maps for degree $2$ and degree $1$ cocycles and draw connections to derivation operators. As an application, we describe Hochschild 2-cocycles satisfying the Maurer-Cartan equation.
        <a class="is-size-7" style="white-space: nowrap;" onclick="document.getElementById('2103.12331v1-abstract-full').style.display = 'none'; document.getElementById('2103.12331v1-abstract-short').style.display = 'inline';">&#9651; Less</a>
      </span>
    </p>
    

    <p class="is-size-7"><span class="has-text-black-bis has-text-weight-semibold">Submitted</span> 23 March, 2021; 
      <span class="has-text-black-bis has-text-weight-semibold">originally announced</span> March 2021.
      
    </p>
    
