    <p class="title is-5 mathjax">
      
        $δ$-$n$-ideals of commutative rings
      
    </p>
    <p class="authors">
      <span class="has-text-black-bis has-text-weight-semibold">Authors:</span>
      
      <a href="/search/?searchtype=author&amp;query=Celikel%2C+E+Y">Ece Yetkin Celikel</a>, 
      
      <a href="/search/?searchtype=author&amp;query=Ulucak%2C+G">Gulsen Ulucak</a>
      
    </p>
    
    <p class="abstract mathjax">
      <span class="has-text-black-bis has-text-weight-semibold">Abstract</span>:
      <span class="abstract-short has-text-grey-dark mathjax" id="2103.11679v1-abstract-short" style="display: inline;">
        Let $R$ be a commutative ring with nonzero identity, and $δ:\mathcal{I(R)}\rightarrow\mathcal{I(R)}$ be an ideal expansion where $\mathcal{I(R)}$ the set of all ideals of $R$. In this paper, we introduce the concept of $δ$-$n$-ideals which is an extension of $n$-ideals in commutative rings. We call a proper ideal $I$ of $R$ a $δ$-$n$-ideal if whenever $a,b\in R$ with$\ ab\in I$ and&hellip;
        <a class="is-size-7" style="white-space: nowrap;" onclick="document.getElementById('2103.11679v1-abstract-full').style.display = 'inline'; document.getElementById('2103.11679v1-abstract-short').style.display = 'none';">&#9661; More</a>
      </span>
      <span class="abstract-full has-text-grey-dark mathjax" id="2103.11679v1-abstract-full" style="display: none;">
        Let $R$ be a commutative ring with nonzero identity, and $δ:\mathcal{I(R)}\rightarrow\mathcal{I(R)}$ be an ideal expansion where $\mathcal{I(R)}$ the set of all ideals of $R$. In this paper, we introduce the concept of $δ$-$n$-ideals which is an extension of $n$-ideals in commutative rings. We call a proper ideal $I$ of $R$ a $δ$-$n$-ideal if whenever $a,b\in R$ with$\ ab\in I$ and $a\notin\sqrt{0}$, then $b\in δ(I)$. For example, $δ_{1}$ is defined by $δ_{1}(I)=\sqrt{I}.$ A number of results and characterizations related to $δ$-$n$-ideals are given. Furthermore, we present some results related to quasi $n$-ideals which is for the particular case $δ=δ_{1}.$
        <a class="is-size-7" style="white-space: nowrap;" onclick="document.getElementById('2103.11679v1-abstract-full').style.display = 'none'; document.getElementById('2103.11679v1-abstract-short').style.display = 'inline';">&#9651; Less</a>
      </span>
    </p>
    

    <p class="is-size-7"><span class="has-text-black-bis has-text-weight-semibold">Submitted</span> 22 March, 2021; 
      <span class="has-text-black-bis has-text-weight-semibold">originally announced</span> March 2021.
      
    </p>
    

    

    
  </li>

